headline_main: Winners and Losers of the Democratic Debate
byline_original: By The New York Times Opinion

abstract: There was little consensus on winners and losers, but political strategists had strong opinions on the biggest moments of the night.
snippet: There was little consensus on winners and losers, but political strategists had strong opinions on the biggest moments of the night.
lead_paragraph: Twitter can’t tell us how, or if, Thursday’s PBS/Politico debate might have changed voters’ minds. But it can give us the perspectives of some people with expertise on primary races: veteran campaign strategists and consultants from both parties.

headline_main: Who Won the Democratic Debate? Experts Weigh In.

abstract: The Democrats keep things fresh with a fight over credentials, crystals and who can beat Donald Trump.
snippet: The Democrats keep things fresh with a fight over credentials, crystals and who can beat Donald Trump.
lead_paragraph: Everyone was getting along so well that for a while, there didn’t seem much point in debating. They agreed that Donald J. Trump was a bad, corrupt president who deserved to be impeached. They agreed that the middle class is hurting, even though the economy is booming. They made flattering references to one another’s remarks.

abstract: It was the last question of the last debate of the year and Elizabeth Warren and Amy Klobuchar, who differ on many policy issues, were united in their answer.
snippet: It was the last question of the last debate of the year and Elizabeth Warren and Amy Klobuchar, who differ on many policy issues, were united in their answer.
lead_paragraph: It was the last question of the Democratic debate on Thursday, and the candidates were thrown a curveball. They could give a “gift” to someone else onstage. Or, in the “spirit of the season,” they could ask for forgiveness.

abstract: Making a case for the nomination, onstage together for one last time in 2019.
snippet: Making a case for the nomination, onstage together for one last time in 2019.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Senator Elizabeth Warren argued that Democrats would defeat President Trump if they “draw the sharpest distinction” with what she called the administration’s corruption — and suggested that Mayor Pete Buttigieg’s high-dollar fund-raising would undermine their ability to do that. Mr. Buttigieg said his party could scarcely afford to hew to such “purity tests” in a race against Mr. Trump.

abstract: Moderators asked the 2020 candidates if they agreed with an assessment made recently by former President Obama about women being better leaders and “old men” needing to get out of the way.
snippet: Moderators asked the 2020 candidates if they agreed with an assessment made recently by former President Obama about women being better leaders and “old men” needing to get out of the way.
lead_paragraph: About an hour into what was a relatively calm Democratic debate Thursday night, moderators turned up the heat by asking the 2020 candidates if they agreed with an assessment made recently by former President Barack Obama: That women should lead, and that problems arise when “old people, usually old men,” fail to get “out of the way.”

abstract: Pete Buttigieg and Elizabeth Warren have assailed each other over transparency issues in the last weeks. Their sparring intensified at the debate on Thursday.
snippet: Pete Buttigieg and Elizabeth Warren have assailed each other over transparency issues in the last weeks. Their sparring intensified at the debate on Thursday.
lead_paragraph: A fund-raiser for Pete Buttigieg held in a wine cellar in Napa Valley elicited the most strident clash between the Democratic candidates at a debate Thursday night after a mostly staid discussion of policy platforms and impeachment, leading to a round of criticism of the mayor that continued into a later exchange about his previous criticisms of Washington experience and his presidential credentials as mayor of a midsize city.

abstract: The seven candidates excoriated President Trump, then turned on one another, as tension between Elizabeth Warren and Pete Buttigieg, building for weeks, broke into the open.
snippet: The seven candidates excoriated President Trump, then turned on one another, as tension between Elizabeth Warren and Pete Buttigieg, building for weeks, broke into the open.
lead_paragraph: LOS ANGELES — Mayor Pete Buttigieg of South Bend, Ind., was repeatedly pushed onto the defensive in the sixth Democratic presidential debate on Thursday night, as several of his rivals challenged his political ascent by bluntly questioning his fund-raising practices and credentials for the presidency in a contentious and deeply substantive forum.
